differ
## [1] 33

The number of rows for a and z are the same. Due to multiplication rules, they have the same product because the 2nd column of z multiplies again with the values from a.

Question 3

The Celcius and Fahrenheit scales are used to record temperature. Find out the formula for conversion between them and write a function called convert.temperature which has the following arguments:

x a single value or vector of temperatures from a character value with the default value “F” (for Fahrenheit) The function should work so that convert.temperature(20) returns the value -6.667 and convert.temperature(20, from=“C”) returns the value 68.

The function should only allow numeric inputs, and should give an error saying Temperature must be numeric if a non-numeric input is supplied. It should also stop with an error saying Invalid input specification if from is anything other than C or F.

a) Give the code of your function

convert.temperature <- function(x, from = "F") {
   if (!is.numeric(x)) {
    stop("Temperature must be numeric")
  }
      if (from == "F") {
        (x - 32) * 5/9
      } else if (from == "C") {
        x * 9/5 + 32
      } else {
        stop("Invalid input specification")
      }
    }

e) Modify your function so that it returns NA for any temperature below -273.15 Celcius, printing a warning as it does so.Give the R code of the modified function 

convert.temperature <- function(x, from = "F") {
   if (!is.numeric(x)) {
    stop("Temperature must be numeric")
   }
   if (x < -273.15) {
    warning("Temperature is below -273.15 Celcius!")
    return(NA)
  }
      if (from == "F") {
        (x - 32) * 5/9
      } else if (from == "C") {
        x * 9/5 + 32
      } else {
        stop("Invalid input specification")
      }
    }

Question 5

Assuming x and y are vectors of length 3, explain the difference between the actions of the following four statements

  • x=y

This assigns the values in vector y to vector x

  • x==y

This checks if the elements in x are equal to the corresponding elements in y

  • x<-y

This would do the same thing as x=y, as it would assign the values in the vector of y to vector x

  • x<(-y)

Checks if each element in vector x is less than the corresponding element in vector y

Question 7

a) Use R to find out what day of the week it was when ChatGPT was first released.

ChatGPT was released on 30 November 2022

gbt <- ("30/11/2022")
gbt
## [1] "30/11/2022"
date <- as.Date(gbt, format="%d/%m/%Y")
date
## [1] "2022-11-30"
ww <- weekdays(date)
ww
## [1] "Wednesday"

b) What date and time (to the nearest hour) was it in New York when the Titanic set sail from Southampton in 1912? Give R code to make this calculation between time zones.

shtime <- "10 Apr 1912 12:00:00"
shtime
## [1] "10 Apr 1912 12:00:00"
titanicsh <- as.POSIXct(shtime, format="%d %B %Y %H:%M:%S", tz="Europe/London")

nytitanic <- format(titanicsh, tz="US/Eastern", format="%d %B %Y %H:%M:%S")
nytitanic
## [1] "10 April 1912 07:00:00"
